04254nam a22005175i 9780773566781DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19971997xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735667817 a10.1515/97807735667812doi  a(DE-B1597)657797  a(OCoLC)1394872720  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ1459.P6bC37 1997eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a971.2/021 aCarter, Sarah A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCapturing Women :bThe Manipulation of Cultural Imagery in Canada's Prairie West /cSarah A. Carter. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1997] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Indigenous and Northern Studies ;v1700tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t“The Honour of a White Woman Is Sacred” -- t“Untold Suffering and Privation” -- tCaptivity Hoaxes and Their Uses -- tIn Sharp Relief: Representations of Aboriginal Women in the Colonial Imagination -- tAlibis for Exclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConsisting of a series of stories, events, and episodes, the book highlights shifting patterns, attitudes, and perspectives toward women in the Prairies. One of Carter's overarching themes is that women are seldom in a position to invent or project their own images, identities, or ideas of themselves, nor are they free to fully author their own texts. Focusing on captivity narratives, a popular genre in the United States that has received little attention in Canada, Carter looks at depictions of white women as victims of Aboriginal aggressors and explores the veracity of a number of accounts, including those of Fanny Kelly and Big Bear captives Theresa Delaney and Theresa Gowanlock, Canada's most famous captives. Carter also examines depictions of Aboriginal women as sinister and dangerous that appeared in the press as well as in government and some missionary publications. These representations of women, and the race and gender hierarchies created by them, endured in the Canadian West long after the last decades of the nineteenth century. Capturing Women fits into a growing body of literature on the question of women, race, and imperialism. Carter adopts a colonial framework, arguing that while the Prairies do not readily conjure up the powerful images of Empire, fundamental features of colonialism are clearly present in the extension of the power of the Canadian state and the maintenance of sharp social, economic, and spatial distinctions between the dominant and subordinate populations. She highlights similarities between images of women on the Prairies and symbols of women in other colonial cultures, such as the memsahib in Britain and the Indian captive in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356678140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773566781423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773566781/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles